Utica, June 22, 1864
Dear Parents,
I have come so far with
the baby. unclear unclear unclear unclear Mary's
and as I've got into so good a place
I will stay till tomorrow to rest a
little. The baby is very good and I
am sure you will all like him.
We started from unclear yesterday
afternoon at about 4 P.M. and
reached here  1 A.M.? today. As it
will be cooler in the afternoon
I will go home then tomorrow
and I shall be very glad to have
some of you meet us at the depot
as Eddie is heavy most as heavy
unclear page is torn Eddie that is according
unclear page is torn Erie and alas
unclear page is torn morning. Hope you have

you got the letters and by then
learned something how I found
Sarah. I do not think she can
get well. I cannot write more
now only to tell unclear that Mamma?
and Ella are well and send

. She will send Danny's? every

Utica Sept 9, 1865
Dear Parents,
The Dr told us this morning
that it would be much better for us
to stay a day or two longer, so we
will not go up tomorrow. We will
write again whey you may expect
us - we will probably stay now to
see a little of the Fair next
week. Perhaps some of the rest
of the girls and Eddie can
come to the fiar and then 
we can go up with them. We
staid at uncle's last night and
are going up again now. We will
not see the Dr till 4 PM tomorrow
and so we will make quite? a
little visit at uncle's. We enjoy
Needs Review

ourselves very much - are feeling
much the same as to our health.
We are intending to go to the
cemetery with Hettie? and Bella
this afternoon. It is a pleasant
cool day - John Pierce? of Aurora
Ill. came to uncle's this morning.
Uncle has gone with him to
Mary now. He intends going up
our way before his return and
he has promised to stop at our
house. Please send with some
of those who are coming down
from the meeting Perkins Elementary
Authentic? for Ellen - one of the
latest editions we have. I told
Mary we had several copies and
Ella need not get a new one.
If you have a convenient opportunity
please send my white skirt and
muslin dress, and one or two collars.
Send me something too. I guess

buff dress Mary thinks so pretty
will be the best - or if it is
very warm and you send me
a thinner dress I shall wnat
a white skirt it will hang
up in my bedroom up stairs
Jennie [[unclear]
I shant need a white skirt

Mrs. Ellis
unclear Tuesday
Dear Parents,
If cousin Mary went up
as she intended with father yesterday
she has told you that I did not
come here till afternoon. I found
Cynthia better than I feared she
was. Eddie came up a little after
dark to call for her to go to a little
unclear unclear page damaged at Wm.? Roberts. He is
looking? well. He says they could go
down tomorrow? or any time that
you could best come down. It snowed
some last evening and froze hard in
the night so that I suppose a sleigh
could come tho' not very well. If
you do not find it convenient to come
down John James is expecting his friend,
and he has offered to take as many
Needs Review

things for them as he can in their
sleigh and they could take the
rest in the cars. I did not have
but a few moments to talk with
Eddie but will see him today and
write again tomorrow. If you do
not come down with the sleigh I have
half a mind to take Eddie with
Cynthia to visit Miss unclear. What 
would you think of that? We
should be gone a week or so. Sis
is quite willing to go with me
so I am writing to miss M. today
that she may expect us unclear page damaged
Tell the girls I do not feel very 
much encouraged after calling upon
the Dentist. He has appointed
next week Tuesday or Thursday for
me to call again. I did not have
any thing done yesterday.
Jennie
Needs Review

New York, May 5, 1895
Dear Mother,
I would like very
much to know how you are getting
on at home. I am taking a nice
rest but it does not seem that I can
or do do any thing to assist Mary she
rather is doing to make it pleasant
for us. This morning she went with
us to visit the Institution for the
Blind - there are about 40? inmates
Mr. Babcock, The Principal Teacher himself is blind
and also one of the teachers that we saw
while there. Some of the pupils were
scarcely larger than Eddie? and some
were full grown. One of them, a young
man, played on the organ where
there were three banks of keys and two
banks of foot keys and I don't know
how many stops - 20 or more I should say
Needs Review

it was wonderful to see and hear
him. He was a beautiful player and
singer too I think tho' I only heard
him sing with the rest. One young
lady also played with wonderful unclear
unclear and accuracy - afterwards two
young ladies came forward and
sang while the teacher played on
the piano. They had splendid voices
- the younger especially clear and
bird like, I should judge her to be
about 13 or 14 years of age. At the close
all the school sang together "Good Morning."
I wish you could have heard them,
mother, it would have done your
heart good. There were also two little
girls about 10 yrs of age who came forward
and read part? of that unclear. "I am the
time vine?." unclear It was wonderful to hear
them one would almost think they
would forget their blindness in the
fullness of their joy in being able
to learn so much. They did indeed
look happy and neat? and pretty, very
pretty many of them. We waited to see
Needs Review

them go into dinner and it was a
pretty sight many did not seem to feel
their way, but walked or unclear along
without fear. In two weeks from
today they are to have their anniversary
unclear in Steinway Hall.
That will no doubt be exceedingly
interesting. I hope Wm and Sara
will be here to enjoy that or if
they do not come that Anna
will. Cynthia has had no
bad spell since Sunday when
she had a hard one. She rests a
good deal and I think is feeling
pretty well. We are going this
afternoon to Mrs. Tompkins and
it is time to start.
Mr Scott is the only boarder
Mary has now - besides the two
that take breakfast and their
Sunday meals. Mrs unclear daughter
is sick and therefore she is gone.
We want very much to get another
letter from home - hope some one
will write soon - Have you heard
Needs Review

from Eddie to know when he will
be down? It would be very pleasant
to have him here while we are
but I suppose that may not
be. - How does Lewis get on
in the office.
Wish Anna would write
about what things she wishes
us to take home as I have
forgotten - I hear the girls
are waiting! Good bye - with
much love to all - not forgetting
Mary Jane, Frank and Lews' family
all - Your daughter
Jennine Everett

333 W 34th St. New York
May 7, 1875.
Dear Mother & all,
We were very
much delighted yesterday to receive
such a good family letter - we also
had one from brother Eddie at the
same time - it was almost like
seeing you all and having a good
chat. I answered Eddie's letter yesterday
but as Mary had arranged to
take us to Macy's I had no time
to write to you also. We are beginning
to think of going home - our two
weeks will be up next Tuesday, you
know, and I am anxious to know
whether Lewis needs me right away
we are having such a nice time
that it would be pleasant to stay a
few days longer - still we are quite
not - and glad you have had returns - it seems too bad
that it should be
sold for so little
they ask 33 to 35
in the groceries
& this continues
pretty well. I believe 
she stands the sight
seeing better than I.
I shall be very glad
to be safe home
again. We were
all weighed yesterday.
John Eddie 82, sis 85, Dr.
Mary 125, and I 115 all
on the unclear see.
All unclear in love.
Your daughter,
Jennie Everett
Needs Review

willing to start next Tuesday or Wednesday
if it seems beat. We shall hope
to get a letter before then in answer
to this. Tell Mary Jane she was a
very good girl for taking such a long
walk that we might have that letter
and we thank her for it. We are glad Frank?
had so good a time in Utica - he
was indeed fortunate in being there
that Sabbath. the good tidings about
our dear cousins Alick and unclear
makes the prayer [[unclear] more earnest
in our hearts that it may not be
long before our loved boys, Frank, Robbie
and John Eddie shall also decide to come
with us and walk in the pleasant
way of life. So Mrs. Lewis has "gone
home" at last. She has so long been unable
by reason of her infirmaties to
enjoy many earthly things. We can hardly realize how
great and glorious has been the change
to her. Do you know whether cousin
Needs Review

came home? How is Mr. Lewis?
We would like to stop in Utica
and see our relatives there especially
uncle - what would you think of
our doing so? I suppose we shall
not see brother Eddie here as he
writes that he expects to come in two
weeks or so after the final. The little
boys have the whooping cough, he thinks,
and that may hinder him. He hoped
however they would be able to make the proposed
visit home. We have decided to
give up going to Wood Harem this time
as Mary fears it is most too far for
Cynthia during our short visit here.
We met Miss Benjamin and Miss
Lawton at Macy's yesterday they gave
us a kind invitation to visit them
in Hoboken and we think some of
going this afternoon. I was so tired
this morning that I did not get up
till most 10 o'clock when I did and want
Needs Review

breakfast but I'm not sorry it is near
12 now. Tell Anna we had a nice
time in the parlor last evening
Mr. Farier? and his young wife? cam
in early - Mr. Scott did not come at
all. Day before yesterday we were at Mrs
Tompkins and while there met Mr. Evan
Williams with whom we had a very
pleasant little visit. The Welsh people
seem quite rejoiced to have a parlor
again and, as Mrs Jones says, to think
Mr. Davies is "the right man in the
right place."
I would be very glad to be home
next Sunday but it is doubtless best as it
is - we shall think a great deal about
you then - hope the roads will not be
very bad then and that there will
be a good attendance
What do you think about letting
Anna come to stay with Mary if
Sara and William do not wish to come?
I understood you to say that you would
try to share? her in that case and I
told Mary so - I am afraid now that I did
wrong in saying so as there is no word in
reply to the letter I wrote to Wm & Sara
You must think I am writing pretty 
often especially if you do not get the mail
more than once in two or three days. I
am hoping unclear will take this up when he
goes home Sunday, - I wish I knew just
how much Lewis has got set - have you had
proofs get? We did not call at Mr
Howard's about the butter - meant to but did

New York, June 18?, 1877?
Dear Mother,
I went with Mary to see Dr. Houghton, Saturday and he gave me electricity—when I first went there I could not hear his watch tick when pressed against my ear, but after taking that I could hear it held 1/2 an inch off. He thought by that it might be worth while to give it a trial when he shall have returned to the city after his summer vacation. He invited us to called again Saturday if I return this way and he could tell better about the effect of ganvanisem? on me. We were shopping almost all day and so I failed to write. I have not got what I need yet and must go again this A.M. Mary had to get her a suit (overdskirt & polonaise)? she had to get it changed some to fit.

(perpendicular text at top of page and up the right side of the page)
all could share with us—Mary 1-2 lbs of butter fish and pickled them Saturday—there is just one fish left—we also got one large lettuce head (2 cts.)? 3? baskets of strawberries (3 cts. each) one loafd of bread (6 cts) and there is none left for summer?! I think if I come back I'll take some pickled fish and berries home will you have any thing else? I saw nice pine apples 4 for a quarter Sat eve. about 11 P.M.—We both send love I hope you will not try to take lunch for meeting, or get very tired.
Jennie Everett

her and so we are, not starting quite so soon as we intended.  I want a boat ride and so am inclined to go by water tonight to N. Haven and get to Sr. Hadley tomorrow morning.  Mary feels pretty well but tires easily and we hope the trip will do her good.  We took tea Saturday with Mrs. Jones and yesterday we went to church only in the evening. I wish I knew how you all are and whether I had better come home this way, if you write, direct Mt. Hot Leone So Hadley, Mass. -- It is just the strawberry season and they are delicious. Mr unclear, 
South Hadley Mass
June 19, 1899
Dear Mother,
We reached here safely
about 9 A.M. today and received
a very kind cordial welcome. We
started from New York about 11 P.M.
yesterday by boat for New Haven
and got tickets on the boat through
to Smith's Ferry for 3.15 each with
berths. We rested pretty well and I
slept a good deal, more the Mary
I suppose, as the light troubled her
somewhat. We reached New Haven a
little before four and took the unclear then
eight by the boat it was a slow train.
Springfield is 12 miles from New Haven
and about 15 from Smiths Ferry. When
near Smith's Ferry it began to rain
Needs Review

and continued till we reached the
Seminary. The Ferry is on Connecticut
River and we got into a stage which
was driven upon a movable platform and
then towed across by means of
wires stretched across the river. We
were alone in the stage except one
young lady a member of the Sem?
here. Mary had quite a conversation
with her and our ride seemed short.
I enquired for Miss Nulting (my class
mate who stays here) and found I was
the first of my class to arrive -
I must? close now as the 
mail leaves in 5 minutes. We
are well and glad we came.
Mary and Jennie
Needs Review

New York     June
Dear Mother,
You may be sure yours was very welcome this morning as it contained our first words from home since I left.  But we are saddened indeed to hear off the death of our good friend Heyt Jones.  How much She will be missed by all.  Poor Mrs. Jones.  my heart aches for her!  She knows that with him all is well.  He was a good man, doing faithfully his work at home and in the church, and I am sure to him have been spoken the blessed words "Well done, good and 
There was a great card there I have bought me a cambric pole nois, parasol ?? and white skirt besides.  watch chain, stockings &C &C.  I do not know what Dr. Houghton will charge.  Mary is not feeling very strong, but she is well.  I think she has not thin enough dresses and she has ?? on her brown silk this P.M.
Needs Review

faithful servant."  But it is hard to realize that he is indeed gone, that we shall see him never again upon earth.  I little thought when I saw him last that the end was so near.  Please give my love to Mrs Jones and assure her of my deepest sympathy.  We shall miss him too oh so much - he was always so kind and true and such a near neighbor.  I should like to have been home and to have done something to help and comfort them.  I cannot realize that it was only the next day after I left.  Was there no one with them?  Were they expecting it?
I fear you all are much worn with thiss and the necessary fatigue of the meeting.  I would like to go right home but have been to see Dr. Houghton since my return.  Perhaps it can be made to ?? with ??

and arranged to see him three times this week and have
a little trial of unclear. We can
tell better then whether to come
back next September or not. We went
this morning but there were so many
waiting to see him and he had
become a good deal exhausted, so
we came away and are going
tomorrow about 9 A.M.
We enjoyed our unclear to South
Hadley very much, I will report
when I get home more particularly.
Yesterday P.M. I went with Mary
to the communion service at her
church - there were twelve received
on confession of faith - four of them
he baptized then. On our return
we called to see Mrs. Jones and
found she had become a grandmother.
David had a little daughter
born Saturday night. They were all
Needs Review

much pleased and Mrs. J.? had gone to
11th St to tell the good news.
Tell Sarah not to try to clean the
sitting room till I'm there to help.
I am very glad Wm has been able
to attend to the lot. Did they do
anything in the A.M. in difference? to
paying the remainder for the monument
How does mother get along nights?? I
think of her every night and wish
I could be with her. I hope you
will all take care of each other
and not get sick. How soon is
John Eddie's school out? Have you
ripe strawberries yet? They are less
plenty here since the cool weather
but we had our fill first. We get
nice lettuce (salad) 2 cts? a head and
we enjoy our meals. Yesterday we took
dinner with Mrs Cole. Last evening
we heard Dr. Ting? in the 34th st unclear page torn
Needs Review

who never complain that they
must speak so loud. Some way
of usefulness may get open to me
tho' my ears may not. I trust you
will not be disappointed to find 
me no better - you hardly expected
it doubtless. It will be a 
satisfaction to have tried.
I have enjoyed my stay
here in many unclear very much
and I hope Mary is no worse for
my coming - certainly we both
were delighted with our visit to
So. Hadley and the renewed intercourse
with friends there
was very sweet. At Mary's suggestion
I was chosen to prepare our class
letter once in two years -this will
keep me within the circle of
their influence somewhat. I
have written two letters suporting?
our meeting unclear and contents of letter
received from the absent - and sent
one to India and one to Albany, N.Y.
Of course I copied a good deal
Needs Review

on one letter into the other - still I
found it took a good deal of time to
write them.
Mary wrote to you about our visit
to the Park - I think I must go once
again before going home and as the
4th is so near I'm tempted to stay
and see what New York is then. Mrs
Jones told Mary of a place to get home
made bread very near here on 10th
avenue - we have had two loaves 
and they proved good - they are
baked in a stove 15 or so loaves
at a time. Friday evening we
called for a loaf, she said she
had baked 100 loaves that day and
they were all gone. Sat. morning
Mary got a fresh loaf and we went
in the evening for another - there
were none left! Today about noon I went
and got her unsure loaf but her oven was
full of more baking - and more still was rising
most ready to go in. There is
no slack business there - if worse
comes to worse I could come to the
unsure, and make bread!
I am ashamed that I had no
more originality that to begin my letter
just like Mary, I didn't see hers! Its
no trouble to guess who - its you I'm
sure - much love from us city folks

Knox Fem. Col. April 2.
Dear sister Sarah.
I have just been writing to Georgie, and now I must write you a short letter before I stop. Jennie has gone out this afternoon, and I am left alone in our little room. I wish you were here with me, and we would have a good talk. Jennie is not very well, and I hope her ride will do her good. She has a good deal to do, especially now, since the meetings have commenced. Our meetings are very interesting. There is, I think, a good
Completed

deal of interest in our school, quite a number of the young ladies seem anxious, and some of them have, I trust, given their hearts to Christ. Yesterday, in addition to the other meetings, a Union-prayer-meeting was opened in one of the largest halls of the place, at twelve o'clock. There were a large number present, we have not been able to attend, as we have a little meeting in the Seminary at the same hour.
We had a good long letter from Sis night before last: they were pretty well. Have you heard from John lately? we do not hear any thing at all from them. I wish you would let us know what you hear from them; we like to hear all about them when you write. Frankly must be quite a boy by this time. How I
Completed

should like to see him. - How do Robbie and baby get along? Tell Robbie that his Aunt Anna thinks of him very often, and wants to see him very much; and he must not forget her. I am going out to walk in a few minutes with Miss Sweetland; we are going to get a couple of tumblers to plant some orange seeds in. I will send you two or three seeds in this letter, and want you to plant them, and we will see who will have the best tree; will you?
Is Aunt Sarah at our house? if she is, please give my love to her. I would like to have another piece like mother's new dress, as I could not find the piece you sent before. Where is Cousin Lettie now? If I knew where she was, I think I should be strongly tempted to write to her.
Completed

Dear Lizzie! she was so well a year ago! I can hardly make it seem as though she was gone from us. How short our life is; we know not how soon we, too, shall be called. Let us seek to be ready at any time. We are only staying here for a short time; soon we shall be called away.
I can write no more now, as it is time for me to go. Write as often as you can, wont you, dear, and we will try and do the same.
Much love to all from
Jennie & Anna.
Completed

Remsen, Dec 14, [?]8
Dear Sister,
George has just come - he had a pleasant journey and came without any trouble. He did better than if he had come last night as William was not able to meet him and it was snowing and rather dark. He and Wm are going to the village for his trunk. We are expecting John Eddie as his school closed yesterday..You must have patience with me - I hope to see you next week. I will explain more then - We are pretty well and send love.
Had a splendid good time last Sunday evening.
Completed

Friday morn, 
Dear Mary, 
Cynthia and I have just returned from a week's visit with Eddie and Nate- and Anna is there- went with him. & Sara in the buggy- will probably return tomorrow- Robbie and Maggie also went at the same time with Jenny's horse and buggy- Eddie intends going to New York soon-  Perhaps tomorrow, Ma is getting along well I believe, Cynthia had only two slight spells in June the last Sat. morning
We are so glad you succeeded with that arrangement at the lodge,
Completed

South Hadley, Jan. 5: 1850.
Dear Father:
I received your kind letter last evening and hasten to answer it. It was such a treat to receive one from my father. Dear father, I thank you very much for your sacrifice of those precious moments spent in writing that well commenced family letter. Oh! that the others had been so faithful, then indeed it would almost seem as though I had seen all our pleasant family circle at my own loved home. That "ancient scrap" as you call it has however furnished me with a very pleasant chat with my father and mother and a short one with Sarah my sister. The regulations of our school I have already learned to love, not not only as being necessary but as the best that could be formed for a school of this size and character. There have been instances of girls here becoming sick in consequence of receiving food from their friends or purchasing, and therefor they made a rule in relation to it, so it has been with the other requirments of this nature; they have formed them as the case required, for example, our dining hall has been rather noisy before sitting down to the table and after rising while we were going out, Miss Whitman requested the young ladies several times to be more quiet, but this had on effect; so a new regulation was added to the others, that we should not speak at all after entering the dining hall until we sit down nor at all after rising from table. I suppose I should say in connection with this that when we go to table we all stand back of our own chairs until the tardy bell strikes, which is a sign for us all to be in our places, and then Miss Whitman makes
Completed

the first move, so you see we may not speak before the benediction is pronounced. I was very glad to hear that you had such an interesting meeting on the first day of 1850. My father's subject, mother told me in her letter, I think must have been very interesting, how I should love to have been there and heard him, even though I could not understand all he might say. Those maps which you mention I think will be a great acquition to your missionary meetings they have them at this church and they add much to the interest and the people get a much better knowledge of the mission fields. We have not had a missionary meeting this three or four weeks At our last we heard a letter from Miss Fisk, (who is graduate of this sem.) and is now in a mission school in Persia. It was was a very interesting letter. there was quite a revival in that school. Miss Hazen our assistant preceptress is going there next fall or rather she leaves this sem. then and it is not yet determined how soon after that she shall start. She is to be married to Mr. Stoddard who has been a missionary there among the Nestorians. I heard him preach one sabbath he is a very interesting preacher and seems very devoted to his labors, but I fear he can not live long, he lookes very poorly. - I must close soon for I may not "cramp mothers part in a little corner." I have about 14 dollars now I shall need 30 to pay my tuition. They are very anxious that we should all have our money ready to pay the first monday of next term I should very glad if you could send me some by that time. We have to pay $1,20 a gallon for oil. It is provided for us here in the sem. we are not allowed to get it at the stores. Wood also is very high. I fear you will think I have been very extravagant with my money but I have
Completed

been as careful as I knew how. I should be very happy if my father would write to me again. I hope if ever I go home again that I shall be a better daughter than I have been for now I know better the value of a father than ever I did before. With much love
I remain your aff. daughter Jane.
Sat evening
Dear Mother:
It is with pleasure that I address you in answer to your welcome letter. I thank you many times for devoting that new years day to writing to me. It was so pleasant hear from father and mother the same time. I was very sorry to hear that Sarah was no better. I do hope that Dr. Fitch will be able to help her. How long since Dr. Gittean has ceased to attend her? Did he consider her case as hopeless or did he think all the time that he could help her? I wish I could pass this next vacation with her, but this may not be and I am content to do that which is for the best. I do not think I should be homesick at all if Sarah was only getting well. It often seems strange to me, how I could ever summon courage to come so far to school and leave her so sick at home. I would write to her to night but my time is so far spent that I fear I cannot. I shall surely write next tuesday evening, if God permits. Tell her to keep up courage as well as she can. I wish Mary could be at home with her, I fear she is very lonely. Tell Gwen that I am very thankful to her for coming to keep my sister company and I shall ever love her for it. I hope Sarah's head will soon be better. Does it affect her eyes any? When next you write please tell as particularly as you can about her. I was glad to hear that Lewis' health is improving, hope he
Completed

has not entirely forgotten his sister Jane. I hope to write to him next vacation and to John also, I have had so little time that I have not done it before. I suppose Lewis has seen my letters that I have sent home so he has no doubts as to my existance. I had not heard of John's promotion. I hope he still remembers his ancient friends. How is Henry's health now I hope he has not forgotten that his name is one of the "letter-writing society" if he is rather remiss in writing. I wish John would join our league, I should be most happy to number my eldest brother among my regular corespondents & Lewis too dont you think he would add his name? I received a letter from Robert last tuesday eve. and also one from Elizabeth and Mary, I had quite a feast that night as you may well suppose. I have not answered Roberts yet. I was writing to Mary & Elizabeth when the letters came so I answered theirs. I do not think I shall be able to get a cloak, I think I had better get a thick sack which will answer the purpose pretty well, I can make that myself, it is almost imposible to get anyone to sew for me unless I got to Northhampton or Springfield which will cost me about $1.00 to go and return. I think I must get me a thick dress this vacation. They have very cold winters here and I must prepare for it. I think I shall get me some corse yarn to knit me some over-socks to walk in that my ancles may not get wet and some cruel to knit something to wear on my neck and also ears, dont you think I had better? Your asking me to favor you with a knowledge of how much my journey cost me reminds me that I have told you nothing about it. The fare form Utica here was $6,42 1/2 I will tell something about my journey when I write to Sarah next tuesday. Tomorrow is to be communion sabbath in this church. Four or five young ladies who see little slip?
